Narratio, 2-11

Pago 106, line 1. Cissim 2.-qualeo . . . oportebat: this remark, though parenthetical, is very significant. The force of the imperfect should be especially noticed, as expressing an obligation belonging both to the past and to the present ; as all ought lo have brem-ie. during the whole time. By this remark Cicero suggests the first point in his defence, because, had all been such, Catiline’s arrest and execution would have been an easy matter. The great difficulty in the case was the fact that the senators were divided on the question.
